# 🌐 AWS VPC — Complete Guide

## What is a VPC?

VPC stands for **Virtual Private Cloud**. It is a logically isolated virtual network within AWS where you launch your resources like EC2 instances, RDS databases, Lambda functions, etc.

Think of it like this:

```
AWS Cloud (entire data center)
└── Your VPC (your private section of that data center)
    ├── Public Subnet  (reception area — internet can reach here)
    └── Private Subnet (back office — internal only)
```

Before VPC existed, all AWS resources were on a flat shared network — anyone in AWS could potentially reach anyone else. VPC solved this by giving each customer their own isolated network.

---

## Why is VPC Needed?

Without a VPC, your cloud infrastructure has no network boundaries. VPC solves these real problems:

| Problem | How VPC Solves It |
|---|---|
| Resources exposed to internet by default | VPC lets you place resources in private subnets |
| No control over who talks to who | Security Groups + NACLs give fine-grained control |
| Compliance requirements (PCI, HIPAA) | VPC provides network isolation required by audits |
| Need to connect cloud to on-premise | VPC supports VPN and Direct Connect |
| Multi-tier app separation | Public subnet for LB, private for app, private for DB |

**Real example at a bank:**
```
Internet Users
      │
  Load Balancer  ← Public subnet (accessible)
      │
  App Servers    ← Private subnet (not accessible from internet)
      │
  Database       ← Private subnet (only app servers can reach it)
```
Each layer is isolated — a hacker reaching the load balancer cannot directly reach the database.

