## Load Balancer

A Load Balancer **distributes incoming traffic** across multiple EC2 instances to ensure no single instance is overwhelmed.

```
Users (internet)
      │
Application Load Balancer  ← public subnet, internet-facing
      │
   ┌──┴──┐
   │     │
  EC2   EC2     ← private subnet, multiple AZs
  AZ1   AZ2
```

### Types of Load Balancers in AWS:

| Type | Use Case | Protocol |
|---|---|---|
| **ALB** (Application) | HTTP/HTTPS web apps, microservices | Layer 7 |
| **NLB** (Network) | High performance, low latency, TCP/UDP | Layer 4 |
| **GLB** (Gateway) | Security appliances, firewalls | Layer 3 |
| **CLB** (Classic) | Legacy — avoid for new apps | Layer 4/7 |

### ALB Key Concepts:

**Listener** — checks for connection requests on a port
```
HTTP:80  →  forward to target group
HTTP:8000 → forward to demoTG
```

**Target Group** — group of instances that receive traffic
```
demoTG
  ├── EC2 i-0abc (10.0.2.5)  healthy ✅
  └── EC2 i-0def (10.0.4.7)  healthy ✅
```

**Health Check** — LB pings instances regularly
```
Protocol: HTTP
Path:     /
Port:     8000
Every 30 seconds → if unhealthy, stop sending traffic
```

**Sticky Sessions** — sends same user always to same instance (off by default)

### Why load balancer is in public subnet but EC2 in private:
```
Internet → LB (public, has public IP) → EC2 (private, no public IP)
```
EC2s are never directly exposed — LB is the only entry point.

