## Security Groups

Security Groups act as a **virtual firewall at the instance level**.

```
EC2 Instance
┌─────────────────────────┐
│  Security Group         │
│  Inbound:               │
│    Port 8000 ← LB only  │
│    Port 22   ← My IP    │
│  Outbound:              │
│    All traffic → 0.0.0.0│
└─────────────────────────┘
```

### Key properties:
- **Stateful** — if inbound traffic is allowed, return traffic is automatically allowed
- **Allow rules only** — cannot explicitly deny (use NACL for deny)
- **Evaluated as a whole** — all rules checked, most permissive wins
- Applied to **ENI (Elastic Network Interface)** of the instance

---

## Network ACL (NACL)

NACLs are **stateless firewalls at the subnet boundary**.

```
Internet
   │
Internet Gateway
   │
NACL  ← checked here (inbound)
   │
┌──────────────┐
│    Subnet    │
│    EC2       │
└──────────────┘
   │
NACL  ← checked here (outbound)
   │
Internet Gateway
```

### Key properties:
- **Stateless** — must explicitly allow both inbound AND return traffic
- Has **Allow and Deny** rules
- Rules evaluated **in order** (lowest number first, first match wins)
- Default NACL allows all traffic

### NACL vs Security Group:

| | NACL | Security Group |
|---|---|---|
| Level | Subnet | Instance |
| Stateful | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Deny rules | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Rule order | Sequential | All at once |
| Return traffic | Must allow manually | Auto allowed |

